\subsection{Demixed phase}  
In the demixed phase, all sites are equivalent but one of the components,
say $\sigma=1$, is dominant.
This means that the density of 1-particles $\rho_i(1)=\rho(1)$ is larger than 
$\rho_i(\sigma)=\rho(2)$ for all remaining particle states $\sigma=2,\ldots,M$. 
In the two-site $\langle i,j\rangle$ problem, we set 
$z_i^{\langle i,j\rangle}(0) = z_j^{\langle i,j\rangle}(0) = 1$, 
$z_i^{\langle i,j\rangle}(1) = z_j^{\langle i,j\rangle}(1) = z(1)$ for particles of
type 1 and $z_i^{\langle i,j\rangle}(\sigma) = z_j^{\langle i,j\rangle}(\sigma) = z(2)$
for all particles of type $\sigma=2,\ldots,M$.
The two-site grand partition function is given by
\begin{eqnarray}
\Xi^{\langle 1,2\rangle} & = & 1 + 2 z(1) + z(1)^2 + 2(M-1) z(2) \nonumber \\
& & + (M-1) z^2(2) + 2 (M-1) j z(1) z(2) \nonumber \\ & &  
+ (M-1)(M-2) j z^2(2) .
\end{eqnarray}
